docs.abstract: The new national security adviser has been quietly taking advice from a few longtime associates. Some have business interests that overlap with the National Security Council.
docs.snippet: The new national security adviser has been quietly taking advice from a few longtime associates. Some have business interests that overlap with the National Security Council.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In the weeks after President Trump chose John R. Bolton to be his third national security adviser in March, Mr. Bolton, a veteran of the George W. Bush State Department whose bellicose manner kept him from a high-level job at the beginning of the Trump administration, engaged in his own sped-up transition process, aided by a handful of longtime associates.

headline.main: Meet the Members of the ‘Shadow N.S.C.’ Advising John Bolton
headline.print_headline: Bolton Is Relying on ‘Shadow N.S.C.’ of His Allies, Worrying Watchdogs

docs.abstract: Mr. McEntee, who was President Trump’s personal assistant, was forced out after his security clearance was revoked, but he will join the campaign as a senior adviser.
docs.snippet: Mr. McEntee, who was President Trump’s personal assistant, was forced out after his security clearance was revoked, but he will join the campaign as a senior adviser.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — John McEntee, who has served as President Trump’s personal assistant since Mr. Trump won the presidency, was forced out of his position and escorted from the White House on Monday after an investigation into his finances caused his security clearance to be revoked, officials with knowledge of the incident said.

headline.main: John McEntee, Trump Aide, Is Forced Out Over Security Issue, but Joins Re-election Campaign
headline.print_headline: Aide Is Forced Out Over Security Issue,  Then Joins Trump’s Re-election Team

byline.original: By Michael D. Shear and Maggie Haberman

docs.abstract: President Trump named John R. Bolton, a hard-line former American ambassador to the United Nations, to replace Lt. Gen. H.R. McMaster.
docs.snippet: President Trump named John R. Bolton, a hard-line former American ambassador to the United Nations, to replace Lt. Gen. H.R. McMaster.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump named John R. Bolton, a hard-line former American ambassador to the United Nations, as his third national security adviser on Thursday, continuing a shake-up that creates one of the most hawkish national security teams of any White House in recent history.

headline.main: Trump Chooses Bolton for 3rd Security Adviser as Shake-Up Continues
headline.print_headline: Trump Chooses Hawk For 3rd Security Adviser As Shake-Up Continues

byline.original: By Mark Landler and Maggie Haberman

docs.abstract: Andrew G. McCabe’s retirement had been expected, but Monday’s departure was abrupt and unannounced. Republicans have accused Mr. McCabe of being loyal to Hillary Clinton.
docs.snippet: Andrew G. McCabe’s retirement had been expected, but Monday’s departure was abrupt and unannounced. Republicans have accused Mr. McCabe of being loyal to Hillary Clinton.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Andrew G. McCabe abruptly stepped down on Monday as the F.B.I.’s deputy director after months of withering criticism from President Trump, telling friends he felt pressure from the head of the bureau to leave, according to two people close to Mr. McCabe.

headline.main: Taunted by Trump and Pressured From Above, McCabe Steps Down as F.B.I. Deputy
headline.print_headline: Deputy at F.B.I., Chided by Trump, Leaves Abruptly

byline.original: By Adam Goldman and Matt Apuzzo

docs.abstract: The president, who is famously fickle, appears to have soured on additional members of his senior leadership team, and some people around him are convinced he could make more moves soon.
docs.snippet: The president, who is famously fickle, appears to have soured on additional members of his senior leadership team, and some people around him are convinced he could make more moves soon.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In his first full cabinet meeting last June, President Trump invited a chorus of gushing praise from his top aides by boasting that he had assembled a “phenomenal team of people, a great group of talent.”

headline.main: ‘There Will Always Be Change,’ Trump Says as More Personnel Shake-Ups Loom
headline.print_headline: Six Gone From ‘Phenomenal Team’; How Many More to Go?

byline.original: By Michael D. Shear and Maggie Haberman

docs.abstract: After an argument on the independence of executive branch officials, Mr. Rosenstein made his Supreme Court debut in a separate sentencing case.
docs.snippet: After an argument on the independence of executive branch officials, Mr. Rosenstein made his Supreme Court debut in a separate sentencing case.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — On Monday morning, the Supreme Court heard an argument that touched on the president’s power to fire subordinates. In the afternoon, Deputy Attorney General Rod J. Rosenstein, who has been the subject of reports that President Trump wants to fire him, argued before the justices.

headline.main: Rod Rosenstein Makes a Timely Supreme Court Appearance
headline.print_headline: After Arguments on the Appointments Clause, a Timely Appearance in Court

docs.abstract: The violent end of Col. Muammar el-Qaddafi, an unexpected turn of events after he gave up his nuclear program, is likely to serve as a cautionary tale for Kim Jong-un.
docs.snippet: The violent end of Col. Muammar el-Qaddafi, an unexpected turn of events after he gave up his nuclear program, is likely to serve as a cautionary tale for Kim Jong-un.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When John R. Bolton looks at North Korea, he sees Libya. It is not a perfect comparison, he acknowledges, but if there is a model for how to peacefully rid a hostile dictatorial state of its nuclear program, he points to the disarming of Libya some 15 years ago.

headline.main: Libya as a Model for Disarmament? North Korea May See It Very Differently
headline.print_headline: Disarmament, Nuclear Deterrents And the Fall of Libya

docs.abstract: In some ways, President Trump, who came of age during the Cuban Missile Crisis and has long given thought to North Korea, has been preparing for this encounter his entire adult life.
docs.snippet: In some ways, President Trump, who came of age during the Cuban Missile Crisis and has long given thought to North Korea, has been preparing for this encounter his entire adult life.
docs.lead_paragraph: SINGAPORE — When President Trump declared that he did not really need to prepare for his legacy-defining meeting with North Korea’s leader, he drew sighs or snickers from veterans of past negotiations. But he had a point: In his own unorthodox way, Mr. Trump has been preparing for this encounter his entire adult life.

headline.main: Meeting With Kim Tests Trump’s Dealmaking Swagger
headline.print_headline: No Need for Him to Prepare to Meet Kim? Trump May Have a Point

docs.abstract: The court vacated an appeals court ruling that had allowed a teenager to obtain an abortion, saying the dispute was moot.
docs.snippet: The court vacated an appeals court ruling that had allowed a teenager to obtain an abortion, saying the dispute was moot.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Supreme Court on Monday turned away a request from the Justice Department to discipline lawyers with the American Civil Liberties Union for assisting an undocumented teenager to obtain an abortion.

headline.main: Supreme Court Rejects Bid to Discipline A.C.L.U.
headline.print_headline: Justices Deny U.S. Request To Discipline The A.C.L.U.

docs.abstract: At a speech to farmers in Nashville on Monday, Mr. Trump claimed he had cut taxes by $5.5 trillion instead of the actual $1.5 trillion amount.
docs.snippet: At a speech to farmers in Nashville on Monday, Mr. Trump claimed he had cut taxes by $5.5 trillion instead of the actual $1.5 trillion amount.
docs.lead_paragraph: NASHVILLE — President Trump delivered an economic victory lap during a speech to farmers on Monday in which he vastly overstated the size of the tax cuts passed by Congress late last year and played up a rollback of regulations on American businesses.

headline.main: Trump Overstates Size of Tax Cuts in Speech to Farmers
headline.print_headline: Trump Inflates Size of Tax Cuts by $4 Trillion in Speech to Farmers

byline.original: By Michael D. Shear and Jim Tankersley
